---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { siteConfig } from '@/data/site';

const title = 'How to Start an LLC in California (2026 Guide)';
const description =
  'Step-by-step guide to forming an LLC in California. Learn about the $70 filing fee, annual franchise tax, Statement of Information, and everything you need for your California LLC.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#1e3a5f]/90 py-16 sm:py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 text-center sm:px-6">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">
        How to Start an LLC in California
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-blue-200">Updated for 2026</p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-blue-100">
        California is the largest economy in the U.S. and offers unmatched market access. However, its LLC requirements include an annual franchise tax you should know about before forming.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 sm:py-16">

    <!-- Quick Facts -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">California LLC Quick Facts</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          {[
            { label: 'Filing Fee', value: '$70' },
            { label: 'State Agency', value: 'CA Secretary of State' },
            { label: 'Formation Document', value: 'Articles of Organization' },
            { label: 'Annual Franchise Tax', value: '$800 (see note below)' },
            { label: 'Statement of Information', value: '$20 (every 2 years)' },
            { label: 'State Income Tax', value: 'Yes (personal)' },
          ].map((fact) => (
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-gray-50 p-3">
              <span class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500">{fact.label}</span>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm font-bold text-gray-900">{fact.value}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-gray-500">
          Fees and requirements shown are based on our most recent review. Always verify current information at the <a href="https://www.sos.ca.gov/business-programs/business-entities" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">California Secretary of State website</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Affiliate Disclosure -->
    <div class="mb-10 rounded-xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50/50 p-4 text-xs leading-relaxed text-gray-600">
      {siteConfig.disclosureText}
    </div>

    <!-- Why California -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Why Form an LLC in California?</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          California has the largest GDP of any U.S. state and is home to some of the world's most innovative companies. If you live in California or do business there, forming a California LLC is typically required regardless of where your LLC was originally created.
        </p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Massive market access:</strong> Nearly 40 million residents and a diverse economy spanning technology, entertainment, agriculture, and more.</li>
          <li><strong>Low filing fee:</strong> At $70, California's LLC filing fee is among the lowest in the country.</li>
          <li><strong>Strong consumer base:</strong> California's large, affluent population provides enormous market potential.</li>
          <li><strong>Innovation ecosystem:</strong> Access to world-class talent, venture capital, and business networks.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          However, California also imposes an $800 annual franchise tax on LLCs, which is an important cost to factor into your planning.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Franchise Tax Note -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50/50 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">Important: California's $800 Annual Franchise Tax</h3>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
          <p>
            California imposes an <strong>$800 annual minimum franchise tax</strong> on most LLCs. This tax is due by the 15th day of the 4th month after your LLC's tax year begins (typically April 15 for calendar-year LLCs) and then annually each year your LLC exists.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>First-year exemption note:</strong> California previously offered a first-year exemption from the $800 minimum franchise tax for LLCs formed between January 1, 2021, and December 31, 2023. As of our last review, this exemption has expired. However, tax law changes frequently in California. We strongly recommend checking with the <a href="https://www.ftb.ca.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">California Franchise Tax Board (FTB)</a> for the most current rules regarding any first-year exemption or fee waiver.
          </p>
          <p>
            LLCs with gross revenue above $250,000 may owe an additional LLC fee on top of the $800 minimum. This fee ranges from $900 to $11,790 depending on your income level.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Steps -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Steps to Form Your California LLC</h2>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-8">

        <!-- Step 1 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">1</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Choose a Name for Your California LLC</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Your LLC name must not be the same as, or deceptively similar to, any existing business entity registered in California. It must end with "Limited Liability Company," "LLC," or "L.L.C."
            </p>
            <p>
              Search for available names using the California Secretary of State's business search tool at <a href="https://bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov/search/business" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov</a>. You can reserve a name for 60 days by filing a Name Reservation Request (Form LLC-1) with a $10 fee.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 2 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">2</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Appoint an Agent for Service of Process</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              California requires every LLC to designate an agent for service of process. This person or company must have a physical street address in California and be available during normal business hours to receive legal documents.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can serve as your own agent, but many business owners use a professional service for privacy and reliability. Our <a href="/best-llc-services/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">recommended LLC services</a> include registered agent service.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 3 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">3</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">File Articles of Organization (Form LLC-1)</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              File your Articles of Organization with the California Secretary of State. The filing fee is <strong>$70</strong>. You can file online through bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov or by mail.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Information required:</strong></p>
            <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-1">
              <li>LLC name</li>
              <li>Business address</li>
              <li>Mailing address (if different)</li>
              <li>Agent for service of process name and address</li>
              <li>Management structure (member-managed or manager-managed)</li>
              <li>Organizer name and signature</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Online filings are processed faster than mail filings. Standard processing times vary, but expedited options are available for an additional fee.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 4 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">4</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">File a Statement of Information (Form LLC-12)</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Within 90 days of forming your LLC, you must file a Statement of Information with the California Secretary of State. The filing fee is <strong>$20</strong>. After the initial filing, you must re-file every two years.
            </p>
            <p>
              This form provides the state with updated information about your LLC, including its address, management structure, agent for service of process, and the nature of the business.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 5 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">5</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Create an Operating Agreement</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              California law explicitly recognizes operating agreements as governing documents for LLCs. While not filed with the state, having an operating agreement is crucial for defining your LLC's management structure, member rights, and operating procedures.
            </p>
            <p>
              Learn more in our <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">operating agreement guide</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 6 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">6</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Get an EIN</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Apply for a free Employer Identification Number from the IRS. You will need this to open a business bank account, hire employees, and file taxes. The online application is free and takes just minutes.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Ongoing Requirements -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Ongoing California LLC Requirements</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>$800 annual franchise tax:</strong> Due each year your LLC exists in California. Paid to the Franchise Tax Board by the 15th day of the 4th month of your tax year.</li>
          <li><strong>Statement of Information:</strong> File every two years with the Secretary of State ($20 fee). The initial filing is due within 90 days of formation.</li>
          <li><strong>California income tax:</strong> LLC income that flows through to members is subject to California personal income tax, which has rates ranging from 1% to 13.3% (the highest marginal rate in the nation).</li>
          <li><strong>LLC fee for high earners:</strong> If your LLC's gross revenue exceeds $250,000, an additional LLC fee applies. This ranges from $900 (for revenue of $250,000 to $499,999) up to $11,790 (for revenue of $5 million or more).</li>
          <li><strong>Sales tax:</strong> If you sell taxable products or services, register with the California Department of Tax and Fee Administration (CDTFA). The state base rate is 7.25%, but local rates bring the total to between 7.25% and 10.25% depending on location.</li>
          <li><strong>Employer obligations:</strong> If you hire employees, you must register with the Employment Development Department (EDD), carry workers' compensation insurance, and comply with California labor laws.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Costs Breakdown -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">California LLC Costs Breakdown</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>California is one of the more expensive states for LLC maintenance due to the annual franchise tax. Here is a full breakdown of the costs you should expect:</p>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="min-w-full border border-gray-200 text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-gray-50">
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Fee</th>
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Cost</th>
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Frequency</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Articles of Organization (Form LLC-1)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$70</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Name Reservation (optional)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$10</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time (60 days)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Statement of Information (Form LLC-12)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$20</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Every 2 years</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual Franchise Tax (FTB)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$800</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">LLC Fee (revenue over $250K)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$900 - $11,790</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual (if applicable)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Registered Agent Service</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$0 - $299/year</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">EIN (Federal Tax ID)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Free</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certified Copy</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$5 per page</td><td class="px-4 py-3">As needed</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certificate of Good Standing</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$5</td><td class="px-4 py-3">As needed</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Using a <a href="/best-llc-services/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">professional formation service</a> typically adds $0 to $299 on top of state fees, but can save time and help ensure your filing is done correctly. Many services include the first year of registered agent coverage in California.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Tax Considerations -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">California LLC Tax Considerations</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">Personal Income Tax</h3>
        <p>
          California has a progressive personal income tax with rates from 1% to 13.3%. Since LLCs are pass-through entities by default, your share of LLC profits will be reported on your personal California tax return and taxed at your applicable rate. California taxes residents on worldwide income and non-residents on California-source income.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">The $800 Franchise Tax</h3>
        <p>
          The $800 annual minimum franchise tax is the most notable cost of doing business as a California LLC. This tax applies regardless of whether your LLC makes a profit. It is due by the 15th day of the 4th month after your LLC's tax year begins. For most LLCs on a calendar year, that means April 15. The $800 is then due every year your LLC remains in existence, even if you have no income. If you dissolve your LLC, the franchise tax is still owed for the tax year in which you dissolve.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Gross Receipts LLC Fee</h3>
        <p>
          In addition to the $800 franchise tax, California imposes an additional fee based on your LLC's total income from California sources. This fee is calculated on a tiered basis: $900 for income of $250,000 to $499,999, $2,500 for $500,000 to $999,999, $6,000 for $1 million to $4,999,999, and $11,790 for $5 million or more.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Sales and Use Tax</h3>
        <p>
          California's base state sales tax rate is 7.25%, with local additions bringing the total to as high as 10.25% in some areas. If your LLC sells tangible personal property (physical goods), you must register for a seller's permit with the CDTFA, collect sales tax from customers, and file sales tax returns. Many services are not subject to sales tax in California, but the rules can be complex, especially for software and digital goods.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Self-Employment Tax</h3>
        <p>
          Like all states, California LLC members owe federal self-employment tax at 15.3% on their net earnings from the business. Electing S-Corp taxation can help reduce this burden if your income is high enough to justify the additional payroll requirements.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Foreign LLC -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Registering a Foreign LLC in California</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          If your LLC was formed in another state (such as <a href="/start-llc/delaware/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">Delaware</a> or Wyoming) but you conduct business in California, you are required to register as a foreign LLC. California is particularly aggressive about enforcing this requirement.
        </p>
        <p>
          To register, you file an Application to Register a Foreign LLC (Form LLC-5) with the California Secretary of State. The filing fee is $70. You must also designate a California agent for service of process and pay the $800 annual franchise tax just like any domestic California LLC.
        </p>
        <p>
          California broadly defines "transacting intrastate business" to include activities such as having employees in California, maintaining an office in the state, owning property, or regularly soliciting customers in California. Even if your LLC was formed elsewhere, operating in California without registering can result in penalties of $20 per day (up to a maximum penalty), inability to use California courts, and back-assessment of the franchise tax.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is a key reason why many California-based entrepreneurs simply form their LLC directly in California rather than using a state like Delaware. Forming elsewhere adds the cost of dual registration without providing significant benefits for most small to mid-sized California businesses.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">How Long Does It Take to Form a California LLC?</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Processing times for California LLC formation vary based on filing method:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Online filing:</strong> Typically processed within three to five business days, sometimes faster depending on current volume at the Secretary of State's office.</li>
          <li><strong>Mail filing:</strong> Can take several weeks to process due to higher handling times.</li>
          <li><strong>Expedited (in-person drop-off):</strong> California offers expedited processing for an additional fee if you submit documents at the Sacramento office. Same-day or next-day processing may be available.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a formation service:</strong> Services like <a href="/reviews/zenbusiness/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">ZenBusiness</a> or <a href="/reviews/northwest-registered-agent/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">Northwest Registered Agent</a> typically prepare and submit your filing within one business day of placing your order.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Remember that after your Articles of Organization are approved, you still need to file your initial Statement of Information within 90 days. Do not overlook this step, as failing to file results in penalties and possible suspension of your LLC.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Common Mistakes -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Common Mistakes When Forming a California LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Not budgeting for the $800 franchise tax:</strong> Many first-time LLC owners are surprised by this annual cost. Factor it into your business plan from the beginning.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing the Statement of Information deadline:</strong> The initial filing is due within 90 days of formation. Missing it can result in penalties and eventual suspension.</li>
          <li><strong>Not filing the first franchise tax payment on time:</strong> Your first $800 franchise tax payment is due by the 15th day of the 4th month after formation, not at the end of the year.</li>
          <li><strong>Choosing the wrong entity type:</strong> Some California professionals (lawyers, doctors, accountants) cannot form a standard LLC and must use a Professional LLC or Professional Corporation instead.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the operating agreement:</strong> California law recognizes operating agreements as the governing document for LLCs. Without one, default state rules apply, which may not suit your business needs. See our <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">operating agreement guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting about city business licenses:</strong> Most California cities require a separate local business license or tax registration in addition to your state LLC filing. Check with your local city hall.</li>
          <li><strong>Commingling funds:</strong> Mixing personal and business finances can jeopardize your LLC's liability protection. Open a dedicated business bank account immediately after formation.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Advantages and Disadvantages -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Advantages and Disadvantages of a California LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">Advantages</h3>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li>Access to the largest state economy in the U.S. and the fifth-largest economy in the world.</li>
          <li>Very low $70 initial filing fee compared to many other states.</li>
          <li>Massive, diverse consumer market spanning technology, entertainment, agriculture, and more.</li>
          <li>World-class talent pool and innovation ecosystem, especially in Silicon Valley and Los Angeles.</li>
          <li>Strong consumer protection laws that can benefit businesses that prioritize compliance.</li>
          <li>Extensive infrastructure, ports, and transportation networks for product-based businesses.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Disadvantages</h3>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li>The $800 annual franchise tax is a significant cost, especially for new or low-revenue businesses.</li>
          <li>High personal income tax rates (up to 13.3%) on pass-through LLC income.</li>
          <li>Additional LLC fee on gross revenue over $250,000 can add thousands to your tax bill.</li>
          <li>California requires LLCs formed in other states to register and pay the same franchise tax if they conduct business in California.</li>
          <li>Complex regulatory environment with extensive labor laws, environmental regulations, and consumer protection rules.</li>
          <li>High cost of living and office space in many major California markets.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- After Formation Checklist -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">After You Form Your California LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Once your California LLC is approved, complete these steps to get your business fully operational:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>File your initial Statement of Information:</strong> Due within 90 days of formation. File online at bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov ($20 fee).</li>
          <li><strong>Get your EIN from the IRS:</strong> Apply online at irs.gov. It is free and typically takes just a few minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>Open a business bank account:</strong> Bring your Articles of Organization, EIN confirmation, and operating agreement.</li>
          <li><strong>Create your operating agreement:</strong> Finalize and sign your <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">operating agreement</a> with all members.</li>
          <li><strong>Pay your first franchise tax:</strong> The $800 payment is due by the 15th day of the 4th month after your LLC is formed. Pay through the FTB website.</li>
          <li><strong>Register for a seller's permit:</strong> If you sell tangible goods, register with the CDTFA for sales tax collection.</li>
          <li><strong>Get a local business license:</strong> Most California cities require a local business license or tax registration certificate.</li>
          <li><strong>Consider business insurance:</strong> General liability, professional liability, and workers' compensation (required if you have employees) are common needs.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up accounting and bookkeeping:</strong> Maintain accurate financial records from day one for tax compliance and business management.</li>
          <li><strong>Register your fictitious business name (if applicable):</strong> If you operate under a name other than your LLC's official name, file a DBA (Doing Business As) with your county clerk.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Frequently Asked Questions About California LLCs</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">How much does it cost to start an LLC in California?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">The initial filing fee is $70. You must also pay $20 for the Statement of Information within 90 days, and $800 for the annual franchise tax by the 15th day of the 4th month. In the first year alone, expect to spend at least $890 in state fees, plus any registered agent or formation service costs.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Can I avoid the $800 California franchise tax?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">California previously offered a first-year exemption that expired at the end of 2023. As of our last review, the $800 annual franchise tax applies from the first year. Tax laws change, so we recommend checking the California Franchise Tax Board website for any current exemptions. The only way to stop the tax entirely is to formally dissolve your LLC with both the Secretary of State and the FTB.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Do I need to live in California to form a California LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">No. Anyone can form a California LLC regardless of residency. You will need an agent for service of process with a physical address in California. However, keep in mind that if you are not a California resident, you will generally only owe California income tax on California-source income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What is a Statement of Information and when is it due?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">A Statement of Information (Form LLC-12) is a filing that provides the California Secretary of State with updated details about your LLC, including its address, management structure, and agent for service of process. The initial filing is due within 90 days of formation, and then every two years thereafter. The filing fee is $20.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What is the additional LLC fee based on gross revenue?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">California imposes an additional annual LLC fee on LLCs with total income from California sources above $250,000. The fee ranges from $900 to $11,790 depending on your revenue bracket. This is in addition to the $800 franchise tax and is reported on Form 568 (LLC Return of Income).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">How long does it take to form a California LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Online filings are typically processed within three to five business days. Mail filings take longer. Expedited processing is available for an additional fee at the Sacramento office. Using a formation service can help ensure your paperwork is prepared and submitted quickly and correctly.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Should I form my LLC in Delaware or California?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">If you live and operate your business in California, forming in California is almost always the better choice. If you form in Delaware, you will still need to register as a foreign LLC in California and pay the $800 franchise tax, effectively doubling your costs with no practical benefit for most small businesses. Delaware is better suited for businesses seeking specific legal protections or planning to raise venture capital.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Can a California LLC elect S-Corp taxation?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Yes. A California LLC can elect S-Corp taxation by filing IRS Form 2553. Note that California imposes a 1.5% S-Corp tax on net income (with a $800 minimum), which is different from the standard LLC franchise tax. Consult a tax professional to determine if the S-Corp election provides a net benefit in your situation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What happens if I do not file the Statement of Information?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Failure to file the Statement of Information can result in a $250 penalty and possible suspension of your LLC by the Secretary of State. A suspended LLC cannot conduct business, enter into contracts, or maintain lawsuits in California courts. You can revive a suspended LLC by filing the overdue statements and paying all penalties.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

